headline: Microsoft and Amazon Are Downgraded as Redburn Breaks Ranks With Peers
summary: Microsoft Corp. and Amazon.com, Inc. saw their ratings cut to neutral from buy on Tuesday, as Rothschild & Co Redburn’s Alexander Haissl downgraded the stocks for the first time since initiating coverage in June 2022, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  Investors have retreated from AI-related stocks amid unease over stretched valuations.

headline: Energy, Utilities Are the Market's Best Performers—They're Still Down
summary: Over the last three full trading days, the S&P 500 energy sector has lost 0.22%, while the S&P 500 utilities sector is down 0.55%, according to Dow Jones Market Data.  What this tells us is that selling is en masse, but the safe havens aren't getting sold nearly as quickly as growth-focused segments like tech, which makes up a big chunk of the S&P 500.  The cost for insuring Oracle bonds has risen with its five-year credit default swap widening by over 0.6 percentage points since late September, according to Deutsche Bank.

headline: Tech Company Bonds Are Also Slumping
summary: The extra yield, or spread, that investors demand to hold Oracle bonds due in 2055 was recently hovering around 1.77 percentage point, according to MarketAxess.  The spread for Meta Platforms bonds due in 2054 was recently around 1.01 percentage point, up from 0.78 percentage point less than a month ago.  Tech companies like Oracle and Meta have started borrowing heavily in the bond market to fund investments in artificial-intelligence infrastructure.
